column15: Mary Mandy and Hal Moore 772-225-1981 Jensen Beach, FL
column69: Jensen Beach, NW Jack Williams Way 10 m E of NW Main Ave
column153: Adult male agama, orange brown head and tail, dark body except for some gradual tinting in the area around the tail bone. His shape was anole like, a very big one. The first sighting he was quickly moving up a driveway and he appeared to be about 10-12 inches long. The 2nd sighting (when I turned my car around and drove back to see if I had really seen him) he was more curled up but with front paws (paws?) upright, and he did not move. So it was two sightings within about 3 minutes of each other, and he had changed position. Easternmost side of Northwest Jack Williams Way just off Goldenrod Road 1st sighting: running up and stopping on short concrete pad, like a utility vehicle driveway. And on the second sighting he was inside the fenced in area in front of the left front side of the circular utility cover, posing as described in the "Describe What You Saw" section. This area was just behind (East of) Home Depot store and looked like it is on Home Depot property. I did not get out of my car because I did not want to scare him/her.

column99: US Highway 1 southbound exit ramp at C-111 canal
column153: Two Agama agama are reported here, observed on the US-1 southbound ramp exiting to the C-111 canal. One is almost certainly the same animal reported March 28, 2011, by Ron Rozar (record 1346520). This subsequent record (observed 18 months later) includes voucher photographs Ron was unable to obtain at the time. Similarly, one of the photos provided here (IMG_4788) is undoubtedly the same agama reported by Ed Metzger on April 15, 2012, as record #2062426. Differences visible in the August 2, 2012, images included here (IMG_4787 and IMG_4788) confirm that these are two individuals (see date & times recorded on images). US Route 1 southbound exit ramp just north of Mile Marker 116 (17 R 555840E, 2797226 N). Ownership or management of this highway ramp is by Florida Department of Tranportation, and surrounding lands are managed by South Florida Water Management District.

column7: Stefanie Martinelli
column25: Florida Museum of Natural History Herpetology Collection
column69: Palm City, SW Busch St appx 1.14 km W of SW 60th Ave
column153: We seem to have at least 2 established 'groups' on our 5 acre property, each with their own dominant red-headed male - maybe 3 groups. One group is on our back deck and in our laundry room. One is in our horse stable. What may be a third group seems to sometimes overlap one of the other groups. When we moved in 2 years ago, there appeared to be only a few of the lizards present. I'm not sure whether it's due to them being shy or not having been established there for very long. Since then, they seem to have exploded! And have become less shy.

column153: On August 24, in Key Largo, FL, I observed several adult red-headed agamas from the roads in a residential subdivision, west of the the Overseas Highway (US Route 1), near mile marker 105.5 The agamas were active, feeding and basking within a few meters of paved county roads: North Blackwater Lane and Sexton Way. When approached, most fled into nearby yards, hiding in excavations under the concrete slabs of local homes and car ports. However, I saw none on (or crossing) the road surfaces.
